WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:08.470 --> 00:00:11.290
- So we're now on the, into the fifth part

00:00:11.290 --> 00:00:14.463
of the course called, what is to be done?

00:00:15.699 --> 00:00:19.650
And I want to just begin by talking about

00:00:19.650 --> 00:00:23.410
the key features of the
politics of insecurity,

00:00:23.410 --> 00:00:25.980
some of which we addressed
earlier in the course

00:00:25.980 --> 00:00:28.850
and some in the last two lectures.

00:00:28.850 --> 00:00:32.180
But they really shape
the landscape on which

00:00:32.180 --> 00:00:35.420
we have to think about,
what can and cannot

00:00:35.420 --> 00:00:39.090
be done in politics, in
the world as we actually

00:00:39.090 --> 00:00:40.480
find it.

00:00:40.480 --> 00:00:44.253
And so, first thinking about voters.

00:00:45.260 --> 00:00:49.200
One thing that we have learned is that

00:00:49.200 --> 00:00:52.610
local inequalities matter
to people much more

00:00:52.610 --> 00:00:55.430
than global inequalities.

00:00:55.430 --> 00:00:59.690
Bernie Sanders can talk
as much as he likes about

00:00:59.690 --> 00:01:03.930
the top 1% and it will motivate activists

00:01:03.930 --> 00:01:07.150
on the left of the Democratic party

00:01:07.150 --> 00:01:11.720
but most voters really
care about much more local

00:01:11.720 --> 00:01:12.710
inequalities.

00:01:12.710 --> 00:01:14.720
And we talked about this
earlier in the course

00:01:14.720 --> 00:01:18.880
when we were talking
about how capuchin monkey

00:01:18.880 --> 00:01:22.370
experiment was misinterpreted when the

00:01:23.590 --> 00:01:27.640
angry monkey was likened to
the Wall Street protester

00:01:27.640 --> 00:01:31.430
but whether the monkey was
angry because she or he

00:01:31.430 --> 00:01:35.090
was not getting something
that a similarly situated

00:01:35.090 --> 00:01:36.960
monkey was getting.

00:01:36.960 --> 00:01:41.167
The monkey was not troubled
that the researcher

00:01:41.167 --> 00:01:46.167
had a big bowl of grapes and cucumbers.

00:01:47.920 --> 00:01:50.950
So people tend to compare
themselves to similarly

00:01:50.950 --> 00:01:52.509
situated others.

00:01:52.509 --> 00:01:56.370
Oil workers might compare
themselves to coal miners.

00:01:56.370 --> 00:01:59.100
Auto workers might compare themselves to

00:01:59.100 --> 00:02:00.020
steel workers.

00:02:00.020 --> 00:02:03.720
And this is true up and
down the occupational scale.

00:02:03.720 --> 00:02:05.530
I think I mentioned to you, a professor

00:02:05.530 --> 00:02:08.240
would be much more troubled to learn

00:02:08.240 --> 00:02:11.927
that she or he is paid significantly less

00:02:11.927 --> 00:02:16.530
than say, $10,000 less than
a professor in the next

00:02:16.530 --> 00:02:19.980
office than to learn
they're paid half a million

00:02:19.980 --> 00:02:22.790
dollars less than the attorney next door.

00:02:22.790 --> 00:02:25.560
So people tend to make local comparisons.

00:02:25.560 --> 00:02:28.670
And the idea that marked hope for,

00:02:28.670 --> 00:02:31.280
that people would start
to make more global

00:02:31.280 --> 00:02:35.660
comparisons, is not
supported by the research

00:02:35.660 --> 00:02:40.300
of sociologists and social psychologists.

00:02:40.300 --> 00:02:44.470
Secondly, think about
Rick Santelli's rant,

00:02:44.470 --> 00:02:46.320
another illustration of this point.

00:02:46.320 --> 00:02:49.772
This is the famous rant
on the Chicago Mercantile

00:02:49.772 --> 00:02:53.817
Exchange right after
the Obama Administration

00:02:53.817 --> 00:02:57.850
came into office and had
started talking about

00:02:57.850 --> 00:03:01.120
minor mortgage relief for homeowners.

00:03:01.120 --> 00:03:04.160
Nothing like John
Geanakoplos was proposing,

00:03:04.160 --> 00:03:07.290
but nonetheless he was proposing reducing

00:03:07.290 --> 00:03:10.870
interest rates at least
for a time on peoples loans

00:03:10.870 --> 00:03:14.430
and it produced a lot of
rage that was articulated

00:03:14.430 --> 00:03:17.418
in that video I showed you.

00:03:17.418 --> 00:03:21.480
At the end of it, his
calling for a tea party

00:03:21.480 --> 00:03:26.177
and people credit the formation
of the tea party with...

00:03:29.107 --> 00:03:34.107
As being, if you like,
catalyzed by Rick Santelli's

00:03:34.270 --> 00:03:37.100
rant on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.

00:03:37.100 --> 00:03:40.230
And you might also recall
that one of the things

00:03:40.230 --> 00:03:43.390
he complained about was, he
said, it's a moral hazard.

00:03:43.390 --> 00:03:45.410
It's a moral hazard.

00:03:45.410 --> 00:03:47.630
But notice of course,
bailing out the banks

00:03:47.630 --> 00:03:49.850
is also a moral hazard, right?

00:03:49.850 --> 00:03:52.480
Bailing out the banks is
giving banks the incentive

00:03:52.480 --> 00:03:54.930
to gamble with taxpayer's money.

00:03:54.930 --> 00:03:58.140
So while it may be a
moral hazard to bail out

00:03:58.140 --> 00:04:01.220
the homeowner's, it's
no less, you might say

00:04:01.220 --> 00:04:05.110
in some ways it's more
consequential moral hazard

00:04:05.110 --> 00:04:06.180
to bail out the banks.

00:04:06.180 --> 00:04:09.620
Nonetheless, what enraged him was that

00:04:10.770 --> 00:04:13.660
do you wanna pay for your
neighbor's mortgage?,

00:04:13.660 --> 00:04:15.040
he rhetorically said.

00:04:15.040 --> 00:04:19.783
So again, local comparisons
that matter to people.

00:04:21.400 --> 00:04:24.070
Think about the difference
between the Trump

00:04:24.070 --> 00:04:28.203
and Sander's campaigns on this question of

00:04:28.203 --> 00:04:31.913
who people compare themselves with.

00:04:32.790 --> 00:04:36.170
In many ways Trump and
Sanders ran a populist

00:04:36.170 --> 00:04:38.733
campaigns in the 2016 election.

00:04:38.733 --> 00:04:43.733
They attacked Wall Street
elites for being corrupt.

00:04:45.019 --> 00:04:49.080
But a difference was that Sanders talked

00:04:49.080 --> 00:04:52.770
a lot about inequality
whereas Trump did not.

00:04:52.770 --> 00:04:56.000
Trump never promised to reduce inequality.

00:04:56.000 --> 00:04:59.610
He never, as I said, even said

00:04:59.610 --> 00:05:02.361
what Ronald Reagan had said, that he wants

00:05:02.361 --> 00:05:03.870
America to be a country in which everybody

00:05:03.870 --> 00:05:05.245
can get rich.

00:05:05.245 --> 00:05:09.751
All he said was that, you
people have been screwed.

00:05:09.751 --> 00:05:11.940
You people have been...

00:05:14.110 --> 00:05:16.760
Left behind by the...

00:05:18.530 --> 00:05:21.040
By the policies of foolish elites,

00:05:21.040 --> 00:05:22.400
he calls everybody idiots.

00:05:22.400 --> 00:05:25.500
And I'm gonna put America first and so on.

00:05:25.500 --> 00:05:27.960
And to the extent there
was a fairness argument.

00:05:27.960 --> 00:05:30.868
We talked about this in connection with

00:05:30.868 --> 00:05:33.240
Arlie Hochschild's
narrative of cutting in.

00:05:33.240 --> 00:05:35.160
Some people have cut in front of me

00:05:35.160 --> 00:05:37.460
and taken something that I would otherwise

00:05:37.460 --> 00:05:38.880
have gotten, right?

00:05:38.880 --> 00:05:42.780
Again, very local comparisons that people

00:05:42.780 --> 00:05:43.613
are making.

00:05:43.613 --> 00:05:46.760
They are not thinking about what people,

00:05:46.760 --> 00:05:49.757
very distant from them
in the socioeconomic

00:05:49.757 --> 00:05:52.233
order are making.

00:05:53.243 --> 00:05:56.280
Related to that, closely related to that

00:05:56.280 --> 00:06:00.160
is a loss aversion and in its insecurity,

00:06:00.160 --> 00:06:05.160
often matter much more to
people than inequality.

00:06:05.590 --> 00:06:10.363
Again, think here of Trump's
make America great again.

00:06:11.360 --> 00:06:13.590
Something's been taken away from you.

00:06:13.590 --> 00:06:15.740
We're gonna bring it
back and do something.

00:06:17.820 --> 00:06:21.450
We're gonna recreate something
that had existed before.

00:06:21.450 --> 00:06:24.170
I am gonna bring back those jobs.

00:06:24.170 --> 00:06:25.290
I'm not gonna make you rich.

00:06:25.290 --> 00:06:28.140
I'm gonna bring back those jobs.

00:06:28.140 --> 00:06:30.870
That was the essence of his campaign

00:06:30.870 --> 00:06:34.760
whereas Hilary's was, she
took that other Reagan line,

00:06:34.760 --> 00:06:38.050
American's best days are ahead.

00:06:38.050 --> 00:06:42.830
Sunny optimism which is
a lot harder to sustain

00:06:42.830 --> 00:06:47.830
during an era of endemic
employment insecurity.

00:06:48.030 --> 00:06:50.890
And again, just driving
home the point that

00:06:50.890 --> 00:06:55.090
it's insecurity and the
fear of downward mobility

00:06:55.090 --> 00:06:58.610
that matters much more to
people than their place

00:06:58.610 --> 00:07:01.660
in the distribution of income and wealth,

00:07:01.660 --> 00:07:03.210
globally conceived.

00:07:03.210 --> 00:07:06.830
Remember those data about
Trump primary voters.

00:07:06.830 --> 00:07:11.440
Only a third of whom earned
lower than the median income,

00:07:11.440 --> 00:07:15.302
below $50,000 a head per family.

00:07:15.302 --> 00:07:20.190
Another, 2nd and 3rd earned
between the median income

00:07:20.190 --> 00:07:23.830
and 100,000, and the third
third of primary voters

00:07:23.830 --> 00:07:27.510
not Republican voters
in the general election

00:07:27.510 --> 00:07:29.170
were Trump supporters.

00:07:29.170 --> 00:07:33.657
And in those primaries, so, again,

00:07:35.389 --> 00:07:38.400
middle-class people who feel insecure,

00:07:38.400 --> 00:07:42.910
and this is, what Dan
Markovits' book is about,

00:07:42.910 --> 00:07:47.209
may be just as anxious and mobilizable

00:07:47.209 --> 00:07:51.890
by a populist politician as poor people

00:07:51.890 --> 00:07:53.943
who feel insecure.

00:07:55.370 --> 00:08:00.130
So the insecurity and
loss aversion matter more

00:08:00.130 --> 00:08:03.320
than inequality and
it's local inequalities

00:08:03.320 --> 00:08:07.543
that matter much more to
people than global ones.

00:08:08.400 --> 00:08:10.200
And then we're living in a world in which

00:08:10.200 --> 00:08:13.070
almost everywhere
organized labor is weaker

00:08:13.070 --> 00:08:14.950
than it's been in decades.

00:08:14.950 --> 00:08:17.650
We've seen, in country after country,

00:08:17.650 --> 00:08:21.018
the decline of union
movements, it's way down

00:08:21.018 --> 00:08:23.900
into single digits, in the US,

00:08:23.900 --> 00:08:27.440
and the majority of workers that are

00:08:27.440 --> 00:08:30.580
organized now are in public sector unions

00:08:30.580 --> 00:08:33.570
which do have some political clout.

00:08:33.570 --> 00:08:37.270
We will see next week when
we talk about education.

00:08:37.270 --> 00:08:41.080
But for the most part,
as a force in politics,

00:08:41.080 --> 00:08:46.080
unions have seldom been as weak, if ever,

00:08:47.580 --> 00:08:52.093
in the last 80 or 90 years, if ever,

00:08:53.868 --> 00:08:56.550
as they are today.

00:08:56.550 --> 00:08:58.680
This is particularly pronounced in the US,

00:08:58.680 --> 00:09:01.700
but we saw pretty much everywhere except

00:09:01.700 --> 00:09:05.410
one or two places like
Finland and Iceland, we've

00:09:05.410 --> 00:09:10.070
seen a decline in the
power of organized labor.

00:09:10.070 --> 00:09:13.460
A concomitant to that, business interests

00:09:13.460 --> 00:09:17.960
are stronger than
they've been for decades.

00:09:17.960 --> 00:09:21.210
Partly because of the
collapse of a serious

00:09:21.210 --> 00:09:23.390
alternative out there.

00:09:23.390 --> 00:09:26.920
Communism to the extent
it exists politically

00:09:26.920 --> 00:09:30.640
is now supported by capitalists economies

00:09:32.230 --> 00:09:36.330
in places like China and
Vietnam and so there's

00:09:36.330 --> 00:09:39.680
no real alternative to
capitalism out there,

00:09:39.680 --> 00:09:43.930
which obviously, greatly,
increases the power

00:09:43.930 --> 00:09:45.510
of capital.

00:09:45.510 --> 00:09:48.200
Particularly in an era of globalization

00:09:48.200 --> 00:09:52.260
when it can easily flee, the flying East

00:09:52.260 --> 00:09:55.080
theory that Christina talked about in

00:09:55.080 --> 00:09:56.253
the China lecture.

00:09:57.090 --> 00:10:02.090
And in these, as jobs going
increasingly to technology,

00:10:02.390 --> 00:10:06.260
capital doesn't even need to flee in order

00:10:06.260 --> 00:10:10.140
to increase its leverage over labor.

00:10:10.140 --> 00:10:12.450
So we're living in a world in which labor

00:10:12.450 --> 00:10:15.420
is weaker than its been in living memory

00:10:15.420 --> 00:10:17.870
and business interests are more powerful

00:10:17.870 --> 00:10:20.750
than they've been in living memory.

00:10:20.750 --> 00:10:24.690
And then coming to Thursdays lecture

00:10:24.690 --> 00:10:28.128
of last week, we're also living in a world

00:10:28.128 --> 00:10:31.440
in which political
parties have become weaker

00:10:31.440 --> 00:10:35.460
and more fragmented just about everywhere.

00:10:35.460 --> 00:10:38.840
And this is not something that has gone on

00:10:38.840 --> 00:10:40.730
for eight decades, but it certainly has

00:10:40.730 --> 00:10:44.960
gone on over the past
four decades as labor

00:10:44.960 --> 00:10:47.690
has become weaker, parties on the left

00:10:47.690 --> 00:10:49.740
have fragmented and we saw that

00:10:49.740 --> 00:10:53.208
as induced fragmentation on the right

00:10:53.208 --> 00:10:57.440
in multi-party systems and
all over the democratic

00:10:57.440 --> 00:11:01.280
world, this impulse to
democratize parties,

00:11:01.280 --> 00:11:04.070
to get more and more direct democracy in

00:11:04.070 --> 00:11:06.430
the governance of parties, and in making

00:11:06.430 --> 00:11:09.970
of decisions has greatly weakened parties

00:11:09.970 --> 00:11:12.830
in both multi-party systems and even

00:11:12.830 --> 00:11:16.110
two-party systems and indeed, even the...

00:11:17.670 --> 00:11:21.040
The platonic form of what used to be

00:11:21.040 --> 00:11:22.080
two-party systems.

00:11:22.080 --> 00:11:24.280
The Westminster system between their

00:11:25.400 --> 00:11:28.854
going for referendum between the changes

00:11:28.854 --> 00:11:30.731
in their leadership selection rules,

00:11:30.731 --> 00:11:34.320
between adopting things
like fixed parliaments

00:11:34.320 --> 00:11:38.360
and candidate selection
also being decentralized,

00:11:38.360 --> 00:11:41.040
they have replicated much of the rest of

00:11:41.040 --> 00:11:45.420
the democratic world in
making it much more difficult

00:11:45.420 --> 00:11:48.770
for parties to present, get elected on

00:11:48.770 --> 00:11:52.410
programmatic platforms
and then implement them

00:11:52.410 --> 00:11:54.273
as governments.

00:11:56.480 --> 00:11:59.170
It's a world that's ripe
for populist charlatans

00:11:59.170 --> 00:12:04.170
who exploit insecurity and
promise snake oil solutions.

00:12:04.870 --> 00:12:09.243
So, what is to be done?

00:12:09.243 --> 00:12:11.050
Now at the beginning of the course

00:12:11.050 --> 00:12:14.699
when I prefaced some of these themes,

00:12:14.699 --> 00:12:17.481
in the first few lectures, I also said

00:12:17.481 --> 00:12:20.075
don't get too depressed.

00:12:20.075 --> 00:12:21.971
(class laughing)

00:12:21.971 --> 00:12:26.971
And in many respects, this
is a depressing prospect.

00:12:27.550 --> 00:12:30.590
But what I want to be arguing in these

00:12:30.590 --> 00:12:34.050
last lectures is that,
certainly we shouldn't

00:12:34.050 --> 00:12:37.310
give up hope and there
are ways of thinking

00:12:37.310 --> 00:12:41.190
constructively about
politics going forward.

00:12:41.190 --> 00:12:44.150
And indeed, in some
respects, there are reasons

00:12:44.150 --> 00:12:47.810
not just for hope but even some optimism.

00:12:47.810 --> 00:12:50.280
This was a distinction
Martin Luther King made

00:12:50.280 --> 00:12:51.530
towards the end of his life.

00:12:51.530 --> 00:12:53.300
He said he was no longer optimistic

00:12:53.300 --> 00:12:54.883
but he hadn't given up hope.

00:12:55.930 --> 00:12:58.350
I think there are some reasons to think

00:12:58.350 --> 00:13:01.540
that it might be possible to come up with

00:13:01.540 --> 00:13:05.883
constructive change and
build regressive support

00:13:05.883 --> 00:13:07.830
for it to happen.

00:13:07.830 --> 00:13:12.233
And so that's where we're
headed in these final lectures.

00:13:13.470 --> 00:13:17.940
So, a central message of this final part

00:13:17.940 --> 00:13:21.850
of the course, and if
you like, presupposition

00:13:21.850 --> 00:13:24.960
of much that I'm gonna
say to you, power phrasing

00:13:24.960 --> 00:13:29.140
Immanuel Kant is that,
policy without politics

00:13:29.140 --> 00:13:33.923
is empty, but politics
with policy is blind.

00:13:35.450 --> 00:13:39.230
Policy, politics without policy is empty

00:13:39.230 --> 00:13:43.430
and politics without policy is blind.

00:13:43.430 --> 00:13:47.830
So, let me emphasize that it's not just

00:13:47.830 --> 00:13:51.320
in the real world but in
the academic literature,

00:13:51.320 --> 00:13:54.950
for the most part, people who study policy

00:13:54.950 --> 00:13:57.670
don't think very much about politics.

00:13:57.670 --> 00:14:00.220
They think about what
policies would be good,

00:14:00.220 --> 00:14:01.640
what should happen.

00:14:01.640 --> 00:14:05.270
But they have relatively little to say

00:14:05.270 --> 00:14:08.253
about how they're gonna get it to happen.

00:14:09.990 --> 00:14:12.760
Whereas people who study politics

00:14:12.760 --> 00:14:15.440
tend to explain why what happens happens

00:14:15.440 --> 00:14:19.130
but have way little to say
about what should happen.

00:14:19.130 --> 00:14:24.130
And so there's this sort of
divergence of preoccupations.

00:14:24.310 --> 00:14:27.210
But I think that that is misguided.

00:14:27.210 --> 00:14:29.880
That we really need to think about what's

00:14:29.880 --> 00:14:33.650
desirable in the context
of what's feasible

00:14:33.650 --> 00:14:38.650
and take into account the constraints

00:14:38.710 --> 00:14:41.620
and possibilities that might be offered

00:14:41.620 --> 00:14:44.140
for thinking about policy rather than

00:14:44.140 --> 00:14:46.563
thinking about it in a vacuum.

00:14:47.570 --> 00:14:51.060
So just to give a couple of illustrations

00:14:51.060 --> 00:14:54.850
of policy without politics.

00:14:54.850 --> 00:14:58.370
Perhaps the most influential
book of political economy

00:14:58.370 --> 00:15:01.280
written in the last couple of decades is

00:15:02.650 --> 00:15:07.650
Piketty's Capital in the 21st Century.

00:15:07.670 --> 00:15:10.760
This is the book in which he argues that

00:15:10.760 --> 00:15:15.220
the reason for increasing inequality

00:15:15.220 --> 00:15:18.607
is that returns to capital exceed returns

00:15:18.607 --> 00:15:21.360
to the other factors of production.

00:15:21.360 --> 00:15:24.620
And so, wealth accumulates over time

00:15:24.620 --> 00:15:26.083
at the top.

00:15:27.880 --> 00:15:30.650
Economists debate his data and some ways

00:15:30.650 --> 00:15:34.330
of measuring this but
that's not my concern here.

00:15:34.330 --> 00:15:37.070
The other one I wanna just mention to you

00:15:37.070 --> 00:15:40.110
as examples of these brilliant economists,

00:15:40.110 --> 00:15:42.627
there's no question about
that, but the things

00:15:42.627 --> 00:15:45.360
that he says about politics are...

00:15:49.760 --> 00:15:53.687
Bereft if any serious attention as to how

00:15:53.687 --> 00:15:56.030
they might be enacted.

00:15:56.030 --> 00:15:59.973
So for example, in his
book published in 2014,

00:15:59.973 --> 00:16:02.780
in the penultimate chapter of that book,

00:16:02.780 --> 00:16:06.983
he calls for aggressive
tax on global capital.

00:16:08.360 --> 00:16:10.810
And in the beginning of that chapter

00:16:10.810 --> 00:16:15.810
he does say, well this
might be a utopian idea.

00:16:15.883 --> 00:16:18.160
But we should still put it out there

00:16:18.160 --> 00:16:20.690
for thinking about where we want to get to

00:16:20.690 --> 00:16:24.010
and besides, it could
inform more realistic

00:16:24.010 --> 00:16:29.010
proposals like a
Europe-wide tax on capital.

00:16:31.040 --> 00:16:34.143
Now you might say, well in 2014,

00:16:36.760 --> 00:16:39.130
that wasn't, you know,
it might not have seemed

00:16:39.130 --> 00:16:42.120
a naive thing to say,
as naive a thing to say

00:16:42.120 --> 00:16:47.120
as it is today, but nonetheless,

00:16:49.070 --> 00:16:54.070
in 2018 he has pushed this
idea further with some other

00:16:54.930 --> 00:16:58.170
intellectuals in Europe, publishing what

00:16:58.170 --> 00:17:01.200
they call our Manifesto
for the Democratization

00:17:01.200 --> 00:17:04.270
of Europe, and you can
find it and peruse it

00:17:04.270 --> 00:17:07.300
at your leisure on their website.

00:17:07.300 --> 00:17:10.210
They're calling for the creation of a new

00:17:10.210 --> 00:17:14.383
European assembly that would essentially

00:17:14.383 --> 00:17:17.990
function as a European-wide parliament

00:17:17.990 --> 00:17:21.270
that would have powers to raise revenue

00:17:21.270 --> 00:17:25.820
and manage budgets and it would be...

00:17:27.592 --> 00:17:31.440
The idea is that 80% of the legislators

00:17:31.440 --> 00:17:34.300
would be elected in the national elections

00:17:34.300 --> 00:17:38.390
so when you vote for your MP in the UK

00:17:38.390 --> 00:17:42.626
or Austria, they would
also, not only would they

00:17:42.626 --> 00:17:45.870
go to the British or Austrian parliament,

00:17:45.870 --> 00:17:48.750
they would also participate in this new

00:17:48.750 --> 00:17:50.440
European assembly.

00:17:50.440 --> 00:17:52.430
80% of them would come there.

00:17:52.430 --> 00:17:55.490
The others would come from
the European parliament

00:17:56.410 --> 00:17:59.170
by proportional allocation.

00:17:59.170 --> 00:18:04.100
And they portray this as an alternative

00:18:04.100 --> 00:18:08.130
to the current EU structures
which are so constrained

00:18:08.130 --> 00:18:13.130
by the treaty-based character
of the European union

00:18:14.300 --> 00:18:17.363
which I lectured to you
about some months ago.

00:18:18.310 --> 00:18:21.550
But what do they ignore in proposing this?

00:18:21.550 --> 00:18:25.380
Why is it that the Lisbon Treaty ended up

00:18:25.380 --> 00:18:27.510
with a treaty-based system?

00:18:27.510 --> 00:18:30.430
It was because the more
ambitious proposals

00:18:30.430 --> 00:18:34.590
envisaged at Maastricht
were roundly rejected

00:18:34.590 --> 00:18:37.710
in referendums in Europe.

00:18:37.710 --> 00:18:41.910
And so they had to
actually cancel a number of

00:18:41.910 --> 00:18:44.990
the plan referendums
because they saw the whole

00:18:44.990 --> 00:18:49.990
project of a never closer
union heading for catastrophe.

00:18:50.330 --> 00:18:51.750
And so they retreated.

00:18:51.750 --> 00:18:54.890
The Lisbon Treaty is really a retreat back

00:18:54.890 --> 00:18:58.200
to the idea that while EU is essentially

00:18:58.200 --> 00:19:01.430
a system of intergovernmental treaties

00:19:01.430 --> 00:19:04.270
in its ultimate legitimacy.

00:19:04.270 --> 00:19:07.410
They also argue that the purpose

00:19:07.410 --> 00:19:10.070
of this new European parliament is to do

00:19:10.070 --> 00:19:12.810
things like reduce inequality within

00:19:12.810 --> 00:19:14.430
the member countries.

00:19:14.430 --> 00:19:17.700
But why, if the member
countries in their own

00:19:17.700 --> 00:19:20.820
parliaments can't reduce inequality,

00:19:20.820 --> 00:19:24.210
why would anyone think
that sending them to

00:19:24.210 --> 00:19:26.560
a European parliament would enable them

00:19:26.560 --> 00:19:29.413
to reduce inequality any more effectively?

00:19:30.430 --> 00:19:33.730
So, and if you go and read the website

00:19:33.730 --> 00:19:37.850
that they have there,
which I urge you to do.

00:19:37.850 --> 00:19:40.090
It's certainly an
imaginative and interesting

00:19:40.090 --> 00:19:43.208
proposal in an intellectual sense,

00:19:43.208 --> 00:19:46.010
you will find the thing I said you should

00:19:46.010 --> 00:19:47.340
always be careful of.

00:19:47.340 --> 00:19:49.560
Or should make you watch your wallet.

00:19:49.560 --> 00:19:51.370
The vast majority of it is written

00:19:51.370 --> 00:19:52.940
in a passive voice.

00:19:52.940 --> 00:19:55.790
The vast majority of it said
about what should happen.

00:19:55.790 --> 00:19:57.470
What should occur.

00:19:57.470 --> 00:19:59.053
What needs to happen.

00:20:00.020 --> 00:20:03.430
But of course, we can
talk until we're blue

00:20:03.430 --> 00:20:06.990
in the face about what needs to happen

00:20:06.990 --> 00:20:10.030
without having anything
to say about how to make

00:20:10.030 --> 00:20:10.863
it happen.

00:20:10.863 --> 00:20:13.920
What will be the political
forces that are gonna

00:20:13.920 --> 00:20:16.910
produce an outcome of this kind?

00:20:16.910 --> 00:20:19.210
And when you think back to the literature

00:20:19.210 --> 00:20:22.920
on the European Union, Tony Judt published

00:20:22.920 --> 00:20:27.920
his book in 2006,
post-war, when he warned.

00:20:28.266 --> 00:20:30.940
He said, the problem
with the European Union

00:20:30.940 --> 00:20:33.600
is that it's been an elite
project from beginning

00:20:33.600 --> 00:20:38.600
until end and as soon as
it gets into any trouble

00:20:40.280 --> 00:20:45.280
the popular resentment
of European-wide politics

00:20:46.239 --> 00:20:51.239
is going to erupt and it's
not gonna be pretty to see.

00:20:51.430 --> 00:20:53.530
He turned out to be right about that.

00:20:53.530 --> 00:20:57.470
Adam Tooze in Crash
gives chapter and verse

00:20:57.470 --> 00:21:02.470
of the inability of the
European governing structures

00:21:03.050 --> 00:21:06.620
to come up with policies
that the populations

00:21:06.620 --> 00:21:11.620
in the constituent
countries will live with.

00:21:12.020 --> 00:21:16.620
And so, the nationalists of the countries

00:21:16.620 --> 00:21:20.200
within the European Union is very powerful

00:21:20.200 --> 00:21:24.660
in the idea that it's going
to go away anytime soon,

00:21:24.660 --> 00:21:28.630
I think is implausible.

00:21:28.630 --> 00:21:31.250
And I gave you a reason, if you think back

00:21:31.250 --> 00:21:32.540
to my lecture.

00:21:32.540 --> 00:21:36.510
Among the reasons is that the Europeans

00:21:36.510 --> 00:21:39.610
have contracted out their security to NATO

00:21:39.610 --> 00:21:42.450
over these past several decades whereas

00:21:42.450 --> 00:21:46.372
in the American case, what
built a sense of national

00:21:46.372 --> 00:21:51.020
purpose when we transitioned
from the Confederacy

00:21:51.020 --> 00:21:55.450
to the Constitution was the
creation of a National Defense

00:21:55.450 --> 00:21:58.360
and the funding of
Central National Defense.

00:21:58.360 --> 00:22:02.550
And then the idea that
people would identify

00:22:02.550 --> 00:22:05.550
with the national project rather than,

00:22:05.550 --> 00:22:09.300
what we might call the federal project,

00:22:09.300 --> 00:22:13.920
rather than the states,
that was a transition

00:22:13.920 --> 00:22:17.450
that was set in motion
by the centralization

00:22:17.450 --> 00:22:20.652
of our power over national security in

00:22:20.652 --> 00:22:23.980
the American system at the
time of the Constitution.

00:22:23.980 --> 00:22:25.940
There's never been an analog of that

00:22:25.940 --> 00:22:29.600
and so the idea of an ever closer union

00:22:29.600 --> 00:22:33.050
has largely been a fantasy
of elites for which

00:22:33.050 --> 00:22:35.640
popular support has never been dealt

00:22:35.640 --> 00:22:39.320
and indeed is less likely
to be forthcoming today

00:22:40.350 --> 00:22:45.350
than it has been since anytime since

00:22:45.490 --> 00:22:48.150
the financial crisis.

00:22:48.150 --> 00:22:51.930
So the idea that we can
now create a new European

00:22:51.930 --> 00:22:55.540
parliament that, as they argue in cases

00:22:55.540 --> 00:23:00.540
of disagreement would
actually trump the decisions

00:23:01.600 --> 00:23:06.562
of the European Union
who which are constrained

00:23:06.562 --> 00:23:11.562
by the treaty-based
caricature that strengthens

00:23:11.810 --> 00:23:14.390
national parliament I think is,

00:23:14.390 --> 00:23:17.243
it's an example of policy

00:23:19.700 --> 00:23:23.643
without politics being ultimately empty.

00:23:24.500 --> 00:23:27.770
What about politics without policy?

00:23:27.770 --> 00:23:29.710
Well we have examples of that.

