00:25:14.910 --> 00:25:15.743
Movement.

00:25:15.743 --> 00:25:20.470
It was a movement that
was famously uninterested

00:25:21.305 --> 00:25:24.500
in articulating particular policies,

00:25:24.500 --> 00:25:28.320
in organizing itself behind
any particular agenda,

00:25:28.320 --> 00:25:32.420
but rather its purpose was to express this

00:25:32.420 --> 00:25:36.673
moral outrage at the
bailing out of the financial

00:25:36.673 --> 00:25:41.280
crisis and the inability
of the Obama Administration

00:25:41.280 --> 00:25:44.540
to do much else.

00:25:44.540 --> 00:25:47.220
They were to some extent triggered by

00:25:47.220 --> 00:25:50.150
the Arab Spring Movement
which had gotten going

00:25:50.150 --> 00:25:51.410
that year.

00:25:51.410 --> 00:25:56.410
But they really didn't advocate
any particular policies.

00:25:57.430 --> 00:25:59.630
And indeed if you think about...

00:25:59.630 --> 00:26:03.983
If you think about the
decision to occupy Wall Street,

00:26:04.866 --> 00:26:08.120
it was, you know, unlike,
at least the Vietnam

00:26:08.120 --> 00:26:11.620
protesters went to
Washington where something

00:26:11.620 --> 00:26:13.280
might be done about it.

00:26:13.280 --> 00:26:15.780
Whereas, here they went to New York

00:26:15.780 --> 00:26:19.478
and then spent the following Fall on many

00:26:19.478 --> 00:26:24.210
town and village greens around the country

00:26:25.270 --> 00:26:28.750
but because they lacked
organization or leadership

00:26:28.750 --> 00:26:32.810
or resources, once the cold weather came,

00:26:32.810 --> 00:26:35.560
they soon faded away.

00:26:35.560 --> 00:26:38.460
Now, this doesn't mean
that they were irrelevant

00:26:38.460 --> 00:26:39.910
to American politics.

00:26:39.910 --> 00:26:44.083
They articulated a moral
narrative that was,

00:26:44.083 --> 00:26:48.000
that had a certain kind
of coherence to it.

00:26:48.000 --> 00:26:49.957
You might call it a
reactive moral narrative

00:26:49.957 --> 00:26:52.260
but I'm gonna have some more to say

00:26:52.260 --> 00:26:55.050
about the importance of moral narratives

00:26:55.050 --> 00:26:59.750
in effective distributed
politics later this morning.

00:26:59.750 --> 00:27:03.230
But they had nothing else.

00:27:03.230 --> 00:27:06.430
They had nothing more
than a moral narrative.

00:27:06.430 --> 00:27:09.740
And moral narratives on
their own is not enough.

00:27:09.740 --> 00:27:14.740
Again, this is politics without policy.

00:27:14.800 --> 00:27:18.980
So my agenda today is to get us

00:27:18.980 --> 00:27:22.780
to start thinking about
how, we can think about

00:27:22.780 --> 00:27:25.488
how there can be effective
policies in light

00:27:25.488 --> 00:27:28.791
of what we do know about politics.

00:27:28.791 --> 00:27:33.791
And one phrase that falls to mind is in

00:27:35.540 --> 00:27:39.820
one of John Rawls's less famous writings,

00:27:39.820 --> 00:27:41.590
his Law of Peoples it comes from,

00:27:41.590 --> 00:27:44.510
I believe, the way he first used it,

00:27:44.510 --> 00:27:47.620
this is the idea of Realistic Utopianism.

00:27:47.620 --> 00:27:52.070
And so, the thing about being a realist,

00:27:52.070 --> 00:27:56.820
about politics, in the real
politics sense of realist

00:27:56.820 --> 00:28:00.970
it is the danger of being
a realist is it might

00:28:00.970 --> 00:28:05.394
prevent you from trying
to do things that will

00:28:05.394 --> 00:28:07.853
change reality, right?

00:28:08.925 --> 00:28:12.530
That you'll be so constrained by one sense

00:28:12.530 --> 00:28:15.610
of the politic, you know, the politics

00:28:15.610 --> 00:28:16.950
is the art of the possible.

00:28:16.950 --> 00:28:19.720
You'll be so constrained by the notion

00:28:19.720 --> 00:28:22.010
of what's possible that you won't push

00:28:22.010 --> 00:28:26.113
for policies that might
change what's possible, right?

00:28:27.060 --> 00:28:28.080
So that...

00:28:29.710 --> 00:28:31.890
I think we actually say in our book

00:28:31.890 --> 00:28:36.010
on the Death by a Thousand Cuts that

00:28:36.010 --> 00:28:39.160
real political creativity gets people

00:28:39.160 --> 00:28:42.970
to think that what they
had previously regarded

00:28:42.970 --> 00:28:46.330
as impossible is in fact possible, right?

00:28:46.330 --> 00:28:50.020
That's, you know, you wanna use

00:28:50.020 --> 00:28:51.060
the buzz words.

00:28:51.060 --> 00:28:52.990
You wanna push the envelope.

00:28:52.990 --> 00:28:54.630
Think outside the box.

00:28:54.630 --> 00:28:56.920
You've heard them all before.

00:28:56.920 --> 00:29:00.690
And if you're very
constrained in your thinking

00:29:00.690 --> 00:29:03.002
about what appears to be feasible

00:29:03.002 --> 00:29:06.450
in politics as we know
it today, you will not

00:29:06.450 --> 00:29:10.820
push to change the boundaries of what

00:29:12.140 --> 00:29:15.748
is possible in politics today.

00:29:15.748 --> 00:29:18.773
And so you run a risk
of being, if you like,

00:29:20.052 --> 00:29:24.352
captive of the inability
to think imaginatively

00:29:24.352 --> 00:29:29.080
about ways to change what is possible.

00:29:29.080 --> 00:29:33.010
And so I like this phrase
realistic utopianism

00:29:33.010 --> 00:29:36.230
in that, it conjures up the idea of trying

00:29:36.230 --> 00:29:40.560
to get to a better
place but thinking about

00:29:40.560 --> 00:29:42.420
the steps from here to there.

00:29:42.420 --> 00:29:45.030
You've gotta think about
how you're gonna join

00:29:45.030 --> 00:29:45.950
the dots.

00:29:45.950 --> 00:29:48.790
How you're gonna in fact get policies

00:29:48.790 --> 00:29:52.536
adopted that might change the politics

00:29:52.536 --> 00:29:56.680
on the ground, which I think
is conspicuously missing

00:29:56.680 --> 00:29:59.105
in the proposal for European parliament

00:29:59.105 --> 00:30:01.200
that we just talked about.

00:30:01.200 --> 00:30:04.003
And so to make that case,

00:30:05.160 --> 00:30:06.950
what I'm gonna do today and then I'm gonna

00:30:06.950 --> 00:30:11.400
use this framework in
our remaining lectures is

00:30:11.400 --> 00:30:15.430
talk about what I'm gonna
call building blocks

00:30:15.430 --> 00:30:18.480
of effective distributive politics.

00:30:18.480 --> 00:30:20.670
And there are six of them.

00:30:20.670 --> 00:30:23.021
And I'm gonna spend a little bit of time

00:30:23.021 --> 00:30:24.923
on each of them.

00:30:26.700 --> 00:30:31.063
And I will start with coalitions.

00:30:34.360 --> 00:30:38.420
Very important in politics
to think about coalitions.

00:30:38.420 --> 00:30:41.160
And the reason it's
very important politics

00:30:41.160 --> 00:30:45.060
to think about coalitions
goes back to our discussion

00:30:45.060 --> 00:30:50.060
of the differences between
the median voter story

00:30:50.256 --> 00:30:53.810
and the majority rule divide
the dollar game, right?

00:30:53.810 --> 00:30:57.660
So just to remind you,
the median voter story

00:30:57.660 --> 00:31:02.200
created the expectation that
because the median voter

00:31:02.200 --> 00:31:05.620
is always below the mean
voter, there would be

00:31:05.620 --> 00:31:07.450
downwardly distribution of wealth

00:31:07.450 --> 00:31:11.930
because politicians in search
of the median voter would

00:31:13.950 --> 00:31:18.050
advocate policies that the
median voter would prefer.

00:31:18.050 --> 00:31:23.050
And that was the fear of
19th century liberals.

00:31:23.350 --> 00:31:26.410
It was the hope of Marx in his later years

00:31:26.410 --> 00:31:28.710
when he started talking
about the parliamentary

00:31:28.710 --> 00:31:31.300
road to socialism and it's embodied in

00:31:31.300 --> 00:31:33.030
the median voter theorem.

00:31:33.030 --> 00:31:37.890
The puzzle was that it doesn't happen

00:31:37.890 --> 00:31:39.750
in any kind of systematic way.

00:31:39.750 --> 00:31:42.110
And we thought one
reason for that might be

00:31:42.110 --> 00:31:45.000
that there's another
dimension such as race

00:31:45.000 --> 00:31:46.430
that people care about more.

00:31:46.430 --> 00:31:48.510
And we talked about
Nixon's southern strategy

00:31:48.510 --> 00:31:50.090
in connection with all of that.

00:31:50.090 --> 00:31:54.310
But then we talked about
the majority rule divide.

00:31:54.310 --> 00:31:56.880
A dollar game where we saw even without

00:31:56.880 --> 00:32:01.880
the 2nd dimension any distribution

00:32:02.400 --> 00:32:06.640
of income can be upset by majority rule.

00:32:06.640 --> 00:32:09.390
All you need is three
people and you're off

00:32:09.390 --> 00:32:12.850
to the races with the potential, right?

00:32:12.850 --> 00:32:15.860
So another way of putting
it is that the median

00:32:15.860 --> 00:32:18.910
voter theorem assumes
that all of these people

00:32:18.910 --> 00:32:20.773
are gonna vote together.

00:32:21.610 --> 00:32:24.210
But in fact, you might
get a coalition between

00:32:24.210 --> 00:32:27.410
the rich and the poor
against the middle class.

00:32:27.410 --> 00:32:30.090
So you might get all kinds of coalitions.

00:32:30.090 --> 00:32:32.730
And that means that no...

00:32:34.800 --> 00:32:38.370
No distribution of income and wealth is

00:32:40.060 --> 00:32:44.360
not potentially vulnerable to being upset

00:32:44.360 --> 00:32:45.810
by majority rule.

00:32:45.810 --> 00:32:48.870
And an example of this, we spent some time

00:32:48.870 --> 00:32:51.310
on early in the course, was the campaign

00:32:51.310 --> 00:32:54.683
to repeal the estate tax
which is just about money.

00:32:55.570 --> 00:32:58.158
It was just one divisible good.

00:32:58.158 --> 00:33:02.490
And so, that's clearly not the case that

00:33:04.536 --> 00:33:07.460
a 2nd dimension or anything like that

00:33:07.460 --> 00:33:09.910
producing the instability.

00:33:09.910 --> 00:33:12.740
So, coalitions are really important.

00:33:12.740 --> 00:33:16.223
You have to think about what coalitions

00:33:16.223 --> 00:33:19.500
are going to support, what it is that

00:33:19.500 --> 00:33:22.590
you're trying to achieve,
and you've gotta think

00:33:22.590 --> 00:33:27.210
about them, both inside the legislature

00:33:27.210 --> 00:33:29.480
and outside of the legislature.

00:33:29.480 --> 00:33:32.480
So if you're thinking
about how to actually get

00:33:32.480 --> 00:33:36.650
a bill enacted in Congress,
you have to not only

00:33:36.650 --> 00:33:41.070
think about, you know,
who is gonna buy off who?

00:33:41.070 --> 00:33:44.290
What deals are gonna be
made to get this bill

00:33:44.290 --> 00:33:46.720
to parliament or through Congress?

00:33:46.720 --> 00:33:48.350
You're gonna have to think about

00:33:51.110 --> 00:33:54.080
building support out there
in the country for it.

00:33:54.080 --> 00:33:56.970
Because there are many, many things that

00:33:56.970 --> 00:34:01.481
politicians are planning to consider but

00:34:01.481 --> 00:34:05.300
in the American case,
for example, the rule

00:34:05.300 --> 00:34:07.810
of thumb is if you're bill does not

00:34:07.810 --> 00:34:11.420
get into the top eight,
which means it will

00:34:11.420 --> 00:34:16.340
be known as HR1-2-3-4-5-6-7 or eight,

00:34:16.340 --> 00:34:20.842
it's not going to actually
make it to the floor.

00:34:20.842 --> 00:34:22.120
It's not going to be voted on.

00:34:22.120 --> 00:34:26.520
How do you get a bill up there?

00:34:26.520 --> 00:34:29.030
We saw, again, with the bill to repeal

00:34:29.030 --> 00:34:32.910
the estate tax that it
took building support

00:34:32.910 --> 00:34:34.970
outside of the beltway.

00:34:34.970 --> 00:34:38.130
Not just inside of the beltway, to get

00:34:38.130 --> 00:34:40.990
many politicians to become cosponsors

00:34:40.990 --> 00:34:43.970
of that bill and see
it is in their interest

00:34:43.970 --> 00:34:45.220
to support it.

00:34:45.220 --> 00:34:47.444
So you have to think
about coalitions inside

00:34:47.444 --> 00:34:50.950
the legislature and
outside the legislature.

00:34:50.950 --> 00:34:55.218
If you think about the
abolition of the slave trade.

00:34:55.218 --> 00:35:00.218
Again, people like this
begins in, it's a story

00:35:01.590 --> 00:35:05.200
that begins in Britain, people
like William Wilberforce

00:35:05.200 --> 00:35:08.560
build a coalition in
the British parliament

00:35:08.560 --> 00:35:11.920
of so called Dissenting
Whigs, the Dissenters.

00:35:11.920 --> 00:35:14.240
And just by chance, this is when,

00:35:14.240 --> 00:35:16.850
this is before the hay
day of strong parties

00:35:16.850 --> 00:35:17.683
in Britain.

00:35:17.683 --> 00:35:19.870
They still had multi-member districts

00:35:19.870 --> 00:35:22.680
so they had much weaker parties.

00:35:22.680 --> 00:35:26.480
And it so happened that,
it behaved much more

00:35:26.480 --> 00:35:28.900
like a European system and it so happened

00:35:28.900 --> 00:35:31.870
that the Dissenting Whigs, for about five

00:35:31.870 --> 00:35:36.110
consecutive elections, in
the mid, between the mid

00:35:36.110 --> 00:35:41.110
1830s and the 1860s, the Whigs held

00:35:41.710 --> 00:35:45.650
the balance of power and were
able, since the Dissenters

00:35:45.650 --> 00:35:48.550
held the balance of power
and because they cared

00:35:48.550 --> 00:35:51.440
more about that than anything else,

00:35:51.440 --> 00:35:54.040
they made a condition of
supporting governments.

00:35:54.040 --> 00:35:55.160
Even Whig governments.

00:35:55.160 --> 00:35:58.610
Even governments that
supported other things

00:35:58.610 --> 00:36:00.263
that they wanted.

00:36:01.230 --> 00:36:03.272
They cared so much about this,

00:36:03.272 --> 00:36:07.730
that they were able to put
it through the legislature.

00:36:07.730 --> 00:36:10.370
But they also built support for outside

00:36:10.370 --> 00:36:11.563
the legislature.

00:36:12.470 --> 00:36:17.167
They threw various anti-slavery societies.

00:36:18.270 --> 00:36:22.076
And indeed, after William
Wilberforce left parliament,

00:36:22.076 --> 00:36:23.210
he spent the rest of his life

00:36:23.210 --> 00:36:26.030
pressing the course
outside of the legislature.

00:36:26.030 --> 00:36:27.720
So, you really have to think about

00:36:27.720 --> 00:36:32.260
building support inside the
legislature and outside.

00:36:32.260 --> 00:36:34.300
A second thing you have to do is not only

00:36:34.300 --> 00:36:36.990
think about enabling
coalitions, but you have

00:36:36.990 --> 00:36:39.920
to think about the blocking coalitions.

00:36:39.920 --> 00:36:43.252
If you're gonna try and enact a policy,

00:36:43.252 --> 00:36:45.760
who's gonna try and stop it?

00:36:45.760 --> 00:36:47.820
And what are they gonna do?

00:36:47.820 --> 00:36:50.260
Because, you know, your coalition

00:36:50.260 --> 00:36:52.271
is not gonna prevail if this ineffective

00:36:52.271 --> 00:36:54.360
blocking coalition.

00:36:54.360 --> 00:36:59.133
Again, we saw, in the
repeal of the estate tax,

00:36:59.133 --> 00:37:02.410
very clever use of enabling conditions,

00:37:02.410 --> 00:37:05.530
and very good strategic anticipation

00:37:05.530 --> 00:37:09.730
of how to head off potential
blocking coalitions.

00:37:09.730 --> 00:37:14.214
And so we saw, for example, they got

00:37:14.214 --> 00:37:18.560
the congressional black caucus to support

00:37:19.650 --> 00:37:22.530
repeal of the estate tax on the grounds

00:37:22.530 --> 00:37:25.600
that it would protect small business

00:37:25.600 --> 00:37:27.920
and particularly in African-American

00:37:27.920 --> 00:37:31.570
communities, and they got
people like Bob Johnson

00:37:31.570 --> 00:37:32.660
to support it.

00:37:32.660 --> 00:37:34.970
Black Entertainment Television

00:37:34.970 --> 00:37:39.078
on the grounds that the first generations

00:37:39.078 --> 00:37:41.950
of wealthy African-Americans

00:37:44.950 --> 00:37:48.377
shouldn't have their, save their

00:37:48.377 --> 00:37:51.820
accumulations tax away.

00:37:51.820 --> 00:37:53.970
They got the support of gay groups

00:37:53.970 --> 00:37:56.640
on the grounds that estate tax

00:37:56.640 --> 00:37:59.500
discriminates against gay people.

00:37:59.500 --> 00:38:01.410
At that time, there was no provision

00:38:01.410 --> 00:38:02.600
for gay marriage.

00:38:02.600 --> 00:38:04.430
Of course, it was not the estate tax

00:38:04.430 --> 00:38:05.977
that discriminated against gay people,

00:38:05.977 --> 00:38:09.180
it was the law of marriage
that discriminated

00:38:09.180 --> 00:38:11.260
against gay people, but it didn't matter.

00:38:11.260 --> 00:38:14.566
They got Frank Blethen, a liberal owner

00:38:14.566 --> 00:38:18.450
of the Seattle Times, to get family owned

00:38:18.450 --> 00:38:21.370
newspapers to support it, because they

00:38:21.370 --> 00:38:25.450
were worried about the Gannett and other

00:38:25.450 --> 00:38:28.800
big multi-national news organizations

00:38:28.800 --> 00:38:30.633
gobbling them up.

00:38:33.652 --> 00:38:36.260
They got the pharmacists to support it

00:38:36.260 --> 00:38:38.470
so that they could get
it through the senate.

00:38:38.470 --> 00:38:40.480
they got small business to support it

00:38:40.480 --> 00:38:42.550
so they could get it through the house.

00:38:42.550 --> 00:38:45.850
Very clever use of all of these groups.

00:38:45.850 --> 00:38:48.470
And then when they thought the potential

00:38:48.470 --> 00:38:52.240
blocking coalitions, the life insurance

00:38:52.240 --> 00:38:56.325
industry, estate planning, life insurance,

00:38:56.325 --> 00:39:01.020
the non-profits benefit
from the tax deductions

00:39:01.020 --> 00:39:05.430
that people make in order
to protect themselves

00:39:05.430 --> 00:39:08.010
from estate taxes.

00:39:08.010 --> 00:39:12.520
And they thought about
unions who generally fight.

00:39:12.520 --> 00:39:16.010
And they came up with
a separate strategy for

00:39:16.010 --> 00:39:21.010
managing every one of
these potential blockers.

00:39:21.290 --> 00:39:24.550
And so, they managed to thread the needle

00:39:24.550 --> 00:39:25.713
in that way.

00:39:26.970 --> 00:39:31.300
If you think about, if you think about

00:39:31.300 --> 00:39:35.120
the abolition of the slave trade.

00:39:35.120 --> 00:39:38.980
They very cleverly, in order to head off

00:39:38.980 --> 00:39:41.960
potential blocking coalition, avoided

00:39:41.960 --> 00:39:44.450
the question of slavery itself,

00:39:44.450 --> 00:39:46.870
and began first with the abolition

00:39:46.870 --> 00:39:49.740
of the slave trade in the North Atlantic.

00:39:49.740 --> 00:39:53.710
And so here, if you think about

00:39:53.710 --> 00:39:55.880
the different coalitional possibilities,

00:39:55.880 --> 00:39:57.760
they change greatly.

00:39:57.760 --> 00:39:59.900
Because if you're talking about

00:39:59.900 --> 00:40:02.240
abolishing the slave trade,

00:40:02.240 --> 00:40:06.785
it did not prevent the
cotton manufacturers

00:40:06.785 --> 00:40:10.870
in Manchester from getting cheap cotton

00:40:10.870 --> 00:40:14.320
that came from the American South.

00:40:14.320 --> 00:40:18.655
It did not prevent the
Americans supporting

00:40:18.655 --> 00:40:21.940
after 1808 when it was possible

00:40:21.940 --> 00:40:23.740
to abolish the slave trade.

00:40:23.740 --> 00:40:26.180
In fact, part of the reason you couldn't

00:40:26.180 --> 00:40:28.440
have enforced the abolition
of the slave trade

00:40:28.440 --> 00:40:32.310
without the Americans, and the reasons

00:40:32.310 --> 00:40:35.900
the Americans supported it are not

00:40:35.900 --> 00:40:39.193
very morally appealing.

00:40:40.080 --> 00:40:42.330
There was a racist sense that they

00:40:42.330 --> 00:40:45.660
didn't want a great increase

00:40:45.660 --> 00:40:50.660
in the African-American
population of the US

00:40:51.160 --> 00:40:54.020
And in the American South, it was

00:40:54.020 --> 00:40:55.800
essentially protection.

00:40:55.800 --> 00:40:57.957
There was a domestic slave trade

00:40:57.957 --> 00:41:01.680
that they were interested
in protecting at the time.

00:41:01.680 --> 00:41:06.680
So, it was possible to
put together a coalition

00:41:06.700 --> 00:41:09.490
of strange bedfellows, if you like,

00:41:09.490 --> 00:41:13.460
to get rid of the North
Atlantic slave trade.

00:41:13.460 --> 00:41:17.710
And they left the
battling of slavery itself

00:41:17.710 --> 00:41:19.393
to another day.

00:41:20.620 --> 00:41:21.453
So, again.

00:41:21.453 --> 00:41:23.170
It was possible to put together

00:41:23.170 --> 00:41:25.680
the coalition and head off potential

00:41:25.680 --> 00:41:28.370
blocking coalitions by thinking

00:41:28.370 --> 00:41:31.863
in those kinds of strategic ways.

00:41:33.140 --> 00:41:34.780
A third feature of thinking

00:41:34.780 --> 00:41:39.211
about coalitions is that, hugely important

00:41:39.211 --> 00:41:43.430
to pay attention to business interests.

00:41:43.430 --> 00:41:45.208
This has always been important.

00:41:45.208 --> 00:41:47.750
When we talked about, we talked

00:41:47.750 --> 00:41:49.870
about the new deal.

00:41:49.870 --> 00:41:52.380
While it is true, and I even showed you

00:41:52.380 --> 00:41:54.730
the I welcome the hatred video

00:41:54.730 --> 00:41:58.698
on the second new deal that Roosevelt

00:41:58.698 --> 00:42:02.720
ran on when he was running for reelection.

00:42:02.720 --> 00:42:05.270
As my colleague, Peter Swenson and others

00:42:05.270 --> 00:42:08.190
have documented that most significant

00:42:08.190 --> 00:42:10.350
expansions in welfare states

00:42:10.350 --> 00:42:12.500
have come about with at least tacit

00:42:12.500 --> 00:42:17.220
and sometimes active support
from business interests.

00:42:17.220 --> 00:42:19.963
And if you think that was true then,

00:42:19.963 --> 00:42:22.570
in the world we're living in today

00:42:22.570 --> 00:42:26.310
that I described to you over the lectures

00:42:26.310 --> 00:42:28.660
in this course, when business interests

00:42:28.660 --> 00:42:31.981
are in a position of unparalleled

00:42:31.981 --> 00:42:36.074
power politically, if you're going to try

00:42:36.074 --> 00:42:41.074
to enact policies that affect business

00:42:41.780 --> 00:42:43.910
interests, you better think about

00:42:43.910 --> 00:42:46.083
how they're going to respond.

00:42:47.110 --> 00:42:49.640
Now, that doesn't mean
you should necessarily

00:42:49.640 --> 00:42:51.840
kowtow to business interests.

00:42:51.840 --> 00:42:53.701
But you need to think about,

00:42:53.701 --> 00:42:56.910
will they be an enabling coalition?

00:42:56.910 --> 00:42:59.140
Will they be a blocking coalition?

00:42:59.140 --> 00:43:02.952
Is it possible to divide
business interests

00:43:02.952 --> 00:43:06.290
so that some business
interests are working

00:43:06.290 --> 00:43:10.240
across purposes with
other business interests?

00:43:10.240 --> 00:43:13.908
But in this point of the 21st century,

00:43:13.908 --> 00:43:18.162
the idea that in any capitalist democracy,

00:43:18.162 --> 00:43:23.162
anybody is going to enact policies that

00:43:24.454 --> 00:43:28.950
affect business interests in a serious way

00:43:28.950 --> 00:43:32.820
without contending with business interests

00:43:32.820 --> 00:43:34.430
is a fantasy.

00:43:34.430 --> 00:43:36.780
It's not going to be possible.

00:43:36.780 --> 00:43:39.260
And so you have to think about

00:43:39.260 --> 00:43:42.190
how business interests are going to be

00:43:43.212 --> 00:43:45.360
a factor in whatever it is

00:43:45.360 --> 00:43:49.603
that you're trying to do
or trying to forestall.

00:43:50.760 --> 00:43:52.790
So, for all of these reasons,

00:43:52.790 --> 00:43:56.978
some analytical, some empirical, you have

00:43:56.978 --> 00:43:59.740
to think about coalitions.

00:43:59.740 --> 00:44:02.923
The median voter is not gonna be enough.

00:44:05.460 --> 00:44:09.030
Secondly, moral narratives.

00:44:09.030 --> 00:44:13.360
As I said, when we talked
about occupy Wall street,

00:44:13.360 --> 00:44:16.213
moral narratives matter in politics.

00:44:17.610 --> 00:44:19.093
Why do they matter?

00:44:21.680 --> 00:44:23.570
One reason is implicit in what

00:44:23.570 --> 00:44:26.030
we've already talked about.

00:44:26.030 --> 00:44:28.750
The very fact that purely interest-based

00:44:28.750 --> 00:44:31.230
coalitions are inherently unstable.

00:44:31.230 --> 00:44:32.690
We know that from the majority rule

00:44:32.690 --> 00:44:35.050
divided all again means that something

00:44:35.050 --> 00:44:37.771
else has gotta hold them together.

00:44:37.771 --> 00:44:41.153
If all you're gonna do is say...

00:44:48.050 --> 00:44:49.330
We'll make a deal where you get

00:44:49.330 --> 00:44:52.060
the biggest possible slice, somebody else

00:44:52.060 --> 00:44:55.380
will come along and
offer you a bigger slice.

00:44:55.380 --> 00:44:58.990
And so, you have to think about,

00:44:58.990 --> 00:45:02.410
well, what is it that will get people

00:45:02.410 --> 00:45:05.700
to resist when that somebody comes along

00:45:05.700 --> 00:45:10.163
and tries to recruit you
to a blocking coalition?

00:45:13.820 --> 00:45:15.450
The story I told you when we did

00:45:15.450 --> 00:45:18.910
the estate tax class was that when

00:45:18.910 --> 00:45:20.470
the democrats finally figured out

00:45:20.470 --> 00:45:21.940
what was going on, they came and

00:45:21.940 --> 00:45:23.620
tried to hive off the farmers.

00:45:23.620 --> 00:45:25.610
They're said, we'll give an immediate,

00:45:25.610 --> 00:45:26.443
remember this?

00:45:26.443 --> 00:45:29.680
We'll give an immediate
exemption to farmers.

00:45:29.680 --> 00:45:32.085
And they had a huge fight during

00:45:32.085 --> 00:45:36.522
the subsequent meetings
of the repeal coalition

00:45:36.522 --> 00:45:39.270
because the farmers were
actually being offered

00:45:39.270 --> 00:45:43.083
a better deal by the democrats,
the permanent repeal,

00:45:44.040 --> 00:45:46.470
than the bill was gonna give them,

00:45:46.470 --> 00:45:50.533
which was gonna be this
weird 10 year repeal.

00:45:51.490 --> 00:45:54.720
But they said things when
you interviewed them.

00:45:54.720 --> 00:45:57.150
They sounded like abortion activists.

00:45:57.150 --> 00:45:59.930
They said, how could I
look myself in the mirror?

00:45:59.930 --> 00:46:02.170
How could I tell my child that I had

00:46:02.170 --> 00:46:03.100
been bought off?

00:46:03.100 --> 00:46:07.133
This is a moral crusade, it's
an unjust tax, and so on.

00:46:08.150 --> 00:46:12.433
If you want another
example, many years ago

00:46:12.433 --> 00:46:16.338
I had a call from an academic colleague,

00:46:16.338 --> 00:46:20.710
a philosopher who said they were starting

00:46:20.710 --> 00:46:24.043
a new party, it was gonna
be called the New Party.

00:46:24.043 --> 00:46:26.130
(students laughing)

