When George W Bush in
2005 sought to privatize

00:47:53.500 --> 00:47:55.660
social security, I'll have more to say

00:47:55.660 --> 00:47:57.700
about that in a little while,

00:47:57.700 --> 00:48:00.530
but one of the things he ran into was,

00:48:00.530 --> 00:48:02.940
he couldn't split the coalition.

00:48:02.940 --> 00:48:05.710
They tried by saying the new system

00:48:05.710 --> 00:48:08.681
will not apply to people...

00:48:08.681 --> 00:48:11.740
I think they tried 55, and then they

00:48:11.740 --> 00:48:15.270
tried 50, under the age of
55, under the age of 50.

00:48:15.270 --> 00:48:19.090
And they found that public opinion among

00:48:19.090 --> 00:48:22.530
the elderly didn't move a millimeter.

00:48:22.530 --> 00:48:23.953
So, what did this reflect?

00:48:26.710 --> 00:48:28.970
It reflected the fact that elderly

00:48:28.970 --> 00:48:32.190
people didn't just care
about social security

00:48:32.190 --> 00:48:33.970
for themselves, but for their children

00:48:33.970 --> 00:48:34.960
and grandchildren.

00:48:34.960 --> 00:48:37.689
And so they weren't
sufficiently self-interested

00:48:37.689 --> 00:48:40.349
to be peeled off in that way.

00:48:40.349 --> 00:48:42.490
They were committed to the idea

00:48:42.490 --> 00:48:44.660
that this was gonna be
important to be there

00:48:44.660 --> 00:48:46.760
for future generations.

00:48:46.760 --> 00:48:49.620
Again, they couldn't be bought off just

00:48:49.620 --> 00:48:52.950
on the basis of their self-interest.

00:48:52.950 --> 00:48:56.730
So, an effective movement
is almost certainly

00:48:56.730 --> 00:49:01.090
going to require moral narratives

00:49:01.090 --> 00:49:04.290
that cause people to resist being

00:49:04.290 --> 00:49:07.520
picked off by some blocking coalition.

00:49:07.520 --> 00:49:10.903
And gonna motivate them to do the work.

00:49:11.785 --> 00:49:14.840
To show up at meetings,
to do the leafletting,

00:49:14.840 --> 00:49:19.040
to do the donkey work of moving

00:49:19.040 --> 00:49:21.290
a movement forward.

00:49:21.290 --> 00:49:24.450
Notice it need not be
the same moral narrative

00:49:24.450 --> 00:49:25.780
for everybody.

00:49:25.780 --> 00:49:28.000
If you look again, go back to the case

00:49:28.000 --> 00:49:30.750
of the abolition of the slave trade.

00:49:30.750 --> 00:49:32.510
I keep coming back to the slave trade,

00:49:32.510 --> 00:49:34.470
it's a very interesting example

00:49:34.470 --> 00:49:37.440
because an economist, if there had been

00:49:37.440 --> 00:49:39.920
neoclassical economists around

00:49:39.920 --> 00:49:42.770
at the beginning of the 19th century,

00:49:42.770 --> 00:49:45.364
they would have said it'd be impossible

00:49:45.364 --> 00:49:46.197
to abolish the slave trade.

00:49:46.197 --> 00:49:48.657
The race to the bottom,
all the usual reasons

00:49:48.657 --> 00:49:50.090
would have been given.

00:49:50.090 --> 00:49:52.860
So, I think it's a great
example of realistic

00:49:52.860 --> 00:49:57.073
utopianism, that it actually got done.

00:49:58.224 --> 00:50:01.010
But if you look at the moral narratives,

00:50:01.010 --> 00:50:04.060
actually people didn't share the same

00:50:04.060 --> 00:50:05.630
moral narratives.

00:50:05.630 --> 00:50:08.920
If you look at, for some it was

00:50:08.920 --> 00:50:11.460
religious moral narrative.

00:50:11.460 --> 00:50:14.560
For people like David
Hume, it was a different

00:50:14.560 --> 00:50:15.820
moral narrative.

00:50:15.820 --> 00:50:18.900
There were moral narratives related

00:50:18.900 --> 00:50:21.390
to driving down wages...

00:50:24.690 --> 00:50:25.940
In some countries.

00:50:25.940 --> 00:50:27.320
So, it doesn't necessarily have

00:50:27.320 --> 00:50:29.260
to be the same moral narrative.

00:50:29.260 --> 00:50:32.350
But it has to be a moral
narrative that will

00:50:32.350 --> 00:50:35.290
motivate people and prevent them

00:50:35.290 --> 00:50:37.273
from being picked off.

00:50:41.770 --> 00:50:44.240
So, a third feature of effective

00:50:44.240 --> 00:50:48.760
distributive politics, and
this is hugely important.

00:50:48.760 --> 00:50:52.430
In some ways, very difficult
sometimes in practice

00:50:52.430 --> 00:50:53.530
to think about.

00:50:53.530 --> 00:50:56.963
And this is to pursue proximate goals.

00:50:58.590 --> 00:51:02.228
So, one way of thinking a proximate goal

00:51:02.228 --> 00:51:06.140
is, it's a waystation to a better future

00:51:07.370 --> 00:51:10.770
that will start you on a road to somewhere

00:51:10.770 --> 00:51:13.993
where you're gonna end
up later at a better one.

00:51:14.837 --> 00:51:16.480
So, getting rid of the slave trade

00:51:16.480 --> 00:51:18.580
is a proximate goal on the way

00:51:18.580 --> 00:51:20.420
to getting rid of slavery.

00:51:20.420 --> 00:51:22.440
Of course, it didn't help in the US

00:51:22.440 --> 00:51:24.300
they had a civil war about it.

00:51:24.300 --> 00:51:26.500
But it did help in the British Empire,

00:51:26.500 --> 00:51:29.150
they abolished slavery in almost

00:51:29.150 --> 00:51:31.260
the whole of the empire by 1833,

00:51:32.526 --> 00:51:35.650
including by paying 20 million pounds

00:51:35.650 --> 00:51:38.440
in compensation in various
parts of the empire.

00:51:38.440 --> 00:51:41.740
And then they spent the next six decades

00:51:41.740 --> 00:51:46.740
stamping it out,
including getting involved

00:51:46.784 --> 00:51:49.980
in an undeclared war in South America.

00:51:49.980 --> 00:51:53.575
But pursue proximate goals, move,

00:51:53.575 --> 00:51:57.430
to use an American analogy,

00:51:57.430 --> 00:51:59.530
move the ball down the field

00:51:59.530 --> 00:52:02.610
rather than simply trying to throw

00:52:02.610 --> 00:52:05.123
hail Mary passes every time.

00:52:05.960 --> 00:52:07.553
So, why is this important?

00:52:08.790 --> 00:52:11.560
One is that it's important for sustaining

00:52:11.560 --> 00:52:14.770
coalitions and motivating support.

00:52:14.770 --> 00:52:15.640
So...

00:52:18.280 --> 00:52:21.530
If you have a proximate
goal, that's something

00:52:21.530 --> 00:52:24.200
you can organize your coalition around.

00:52:24.200 --> 00:52:27.580
You can motivate people to fight for

00:52:27.580 --> 00:52:29.080
and to achieve.

00:52:29.080 --> 00:52:32.777
So, if you think about, say, again,

00:52:32.777 --> 00:52:35.680
repeal of a particular tax.

00:52:35.680 --> 00:52:38.050
We've gotta repeal the
tax, you know, we...

00:52:42.433 --> 00:52:44.300
We build the coalition,
we have the meetings,

00:52:44.300 --> 00:52:45.520
we push the bill.

00:52:45.520 --> 00:52:46.890
And then you finally achieve it,

00:52:46.890 --> 00:52:48.340
you can say, we did it.

00:52:48.340 --> 00:52:51.293
You can get people to focus on,

00:52:52.779 --> 00:52:55.290
that can motivate them, and it gets

00:52:55.290 --> 00:52:57.560
them to focus on the result.

00:52:57.560 --> 00:53:00.660
Or if you think about
the civil rights act,

00:53:00.660 --> 00:53:02.593
which we spent some time on.

00:53:03.900 --> 00:53:07.190
The features of the civil rights act

00:53:07.190 --> 00:53:10.545
that were most effectively adopted

00:53:10.545 --> 00:53:13.990
involved well defined proximate goals.

00:53:13.990 --> 00:53:17.760
Like getting rid of restrictive covenants.

00:53:17.760 --> 00:53:20.830
The more nebulous goals,

00:53:20.830 --> 00:53:23.080
such as reducing racial inequality,

00:53:23.080 --> 00:53:26.560
or integrating neighborhoods

00:53:26.560 --> 00:53:29.193
much harder to achieve.

00:53:29.193 --> 00:53:33.764
So, proximate goals are important

00:53:33.764 --> 00:53:38.764
for moving, you know, moving things along

00:53:39.670 --> 00:53:42.140
in the direction that you want to go.

00:53:42.140 --> 00:53:45.230
And for making sure that the best does not

00:53:45.230 --> 00:53:48.493
become the enemy of the good.

00:53:50.261 --> 00:53:53.700
A couple of weeks ago,
we had Gidon Bromberg

00:53:53.700 --> 00:53:56.535
from EchoPeace here to give the

00:53:56.535 --> 00:54:00.370
part of the lecture that
I had not had time to give

00:54:00.370 --> 00:54:02.220
when I talked about when we did the

00:54:02.220 --> 00:54:04.480
Israel-Palestine case.

00:54:04.480 --> 00:54:07.930
And I think I saw some
of you in his lecture.

00:54:07.930 --> 00:54:12.851
Which is on a fascinating topic of using

00:54:12.851 --> 00:54:17.851
economic interdependencies around climate

00:54:18.210 --> 00:54:21.720
to work to move the Israel-Palestine

00:54:22.560 --> 00:54:25.810
conflict in the direction of a resolution.

00:54:25.810 --> 00:54:29.927
And in particular, the
fact that the Jordan

00:54:29.927 --> 00:54:34.680
River is drying up, and the two million

00:54:34.680 --> 00:54:38.530
people in Gaza lack sufficient energy

00:54:38.530 --> 00:54:41.118
to process their own sewage.

00:54:41.118 --> 00:54:44.610
Partly because it's
being denied by Israel,

00:54:44.610 --> 00:54:48.470
the energy, but partly just
an overwhelming demographic

00:54:48.470 --> 00:54:51.799
pressure has started causing a situation

00:54:51.799 --> 00:54:55.000
weighing increases amounts of sewage

00:54:55.000 --> 00:54:57.860
from Gaza being pumped
into the Mediterranean,

00:54:57.860 --> 00:55:01.750
drifting up an forcing desalination

00:55:01.750 --> 00:55:04.443
plants in Israel to shut down.

00:55:05.590 --> 00:55:10.590
It turns out that Jordan has the best

00:55:10.830 --> 00:55:15.810
available geographical situation

00:55:15.810 --> 00:55:19.080
and technology at the
moment for solar energy.

00:55:19.080 --> 00:55:22.353
And so EchoPeace has come up with

00:55:22.353 --> 00:55:27.353
an ingenious plan prepared by solar energy

00:55:28.500 --> 00:55:31.840
that can produce power that will power

00:55:32.910 --> 00:55:35.680
the sewage plants in Gaza,

00:55:35.680 --> 00:55:38.970
which will in turn save Israel money.

00:55:38.970 --> 00:55:41.160
And they've lined the whole thing up

00:55:41.160 --> 00:55:44.240
so that the incentives work for everyone.

00:55:44.240 --> 00:55:47.190
And all of the governments know this.

00:55:47.190 --> 00:55:51.740
And they've even created,
they've raised capital for it.

00:55:51.740 --> 00:55:55.050
So, there's private sector
interest in doing this.

00:55:55.050 --> 00:55:58.670
And in several rounds
of peace negotiations,

00:55:58.670 --> 00:56:02.755
solving this water problem in this way,

00:56:02.755 --> 00:56:04.610
which would actually integrate

00:56:04.610 --> 00:56:07.100
the Palestinian, Israelian, Jordanian

00:56:07.100 --> 00:56:09.060
economies much more and produce

00:56:09.060 --> 00:56:11.840
co-dependencies has come up.

00:56:11.840 --> 00:56:16.050
but it's treated as one of
the final status issues.

00:56:16.050 --> 00:56:18.620
And so the final status issues are these

00:56:18.620 --> 00:56:22.283
difficult questions to be resolved later.

00:56:23.310 --> 00:56:25.540
Something that was never allowed to derail

00:56:25.540 --> 00:56:28.070
the South African negotiations.

00:56:28.070 --> 00:56:32.380
And so Gidon made the case that it would

00:56:32.380 --> 00:56:35.370
be much better to solve
the water issue now.

00:56:35.370 --> 00:56:38.880
And he pointed out that every Middle East

00:56:38.880 --> 00:56:42.670
negotiator that had
tried to get a settlement

00:56:42.670 --> 00:56:46.810
from Clinton to carry,
and others in between,

00:56:46.810 --> 00:56:49.700
subsequently had said,
we should have dealt

00:56:49.700 --> 00:56:51.660
with the water issue.

00:56:51.660 --> 00:56:55.540
So, this is an example, again, that we've

00:56:55.540 --> 00:56:56.800
videotaped that lecture.

00:56:56.800 --> 00:56:59.233
But I strongly urge you to go and see it.

00:57:00.569 --> 00:57:04.221
An example where it would be much better

00:57:04.221 --> 00:57:08.307
not to let the best be
the enemy of the good,

00:57:08.307 --> 00:57:13.307
but use the water issue and resolution

00:57:13.330 --> 00:57:16.850
of the water issue to
take it off the table

00:57:16.850 --> 00:57:20.940
and move the three
countries into a situation

00:57:20.940 --> 00:57:24.930
where they would be
more likely to cooperate

00:57:24.930 --> 00:57:27.283
on other matters in the future.

00:57:28.390 --> 00:57:30.260
But they're hard cases.

00:57:30.260 --> 00:57:33.860
They're really difficult
cases in thinking about

00:57:33.860 --> 00:57:35.500
proximate goals.

00:57:35.500 --> 00:57:39.730
And the hard cases are where if you pursue

00:57:39.730 --> 00:57:43.850
a proximate goal, it might make it,

00:57:43.850 --> 00:57:47.200
instead of being a
waystation to the future,

00:57:47.200 --> 00:57:49.390
it might actually make the future more

00:57:49.390 --> 00:57:52.150
difficult to achieve.

00:57:52.150 --> 00:57:57.150
So, think about Medicare
and social security.

00:57:57.870 --> 00:58:01.310
Social security, we discussed earlier,

00:58:01.310 --> 00:58:05.190
was put in place in 1935, and in order

00:58:05.190 --> 00:58:07.397
to get it through congress, FDR

00:58:08.840 --> 00:58:11.250
had to exclude the Mexican

00:58:12.160 --> 00:58:15.190
agricultural workers, because

00:58:15.190 --> 00:58:17.820
not to do so would have broken

00:58:17.820 --> 00:58:20.010
up his coalition of Southern democrats

00:58:20.010 --> 00:58:22.030
who controlled the committees.

00:58:22.030 --> 00:58:24.870
And so, that was done later.

00:58:24.870 --> 00:58:27.880
It was expanded to cover
those workers later.

00:58:27.880 --> 00:58:30.210
That's, you know, it's not, it wasn't

00:58:30.210 --> 00:58:32.380
great for the people at the time,

00:58:32.380 --> 00:58:35.470
but you could say, well, you know,

00:58:35.470 --> 00:58:39.173
you take what you can get,
and you expand it later.

00:58:42.410 --> 00:58:45.340
Medicare's a harder
case, because Medicare,

00:58:45.340 --> 00:58:49.100
put in place in 1965,
part of the great society

00:58:49.100 --> 00:58:52.350
by Lindon Johnson creates a world

00:58:52.350 --> 00:58:55.640
we live in today where it's much more

00:58:55.640 --> 00:58:58.550
difficult to create universal healthcare

00:58:58.550 --> 00:59:02.587
because the one group that you would want

00:59:02.587 --> 00:59:06.460
in your coalition has
no reason to be there.

00:59:06.460 --> 00:59:07.590
Namely the elderly.

00:59:07.590 --> 00:59:11.990
The elderly, they vote,
they're politically

00:59:11.990 --> 00:59:16.990
active, but they already
have universal healthcare.

00:59:17.172 --> 00:59:21.584
And indeed, if you were
gonna go to any of the

00:59:21.584 --> 00:59:24.510
current plans being proposed,

00:59:24.510 --> 00:59:25.810
which are being underpriced

00:59:25.810 --> 00:59:27.680
from Medicare for all, there would

00:59:27.680 --> 00:59:30.340
be a reasonable fear that Medicare

00:59:30.340 --> 00:59:32.295
benefits were going to be diluted

00:59:32.295 --> 00:59:35.500
for the people who already have them.

00:59:35.500 --> 00:59:37.860
So, that becomes a much harder judgment.

00:59:37.860 --> 00:59:40.210
It doesn't mean that they shouldn't have

00:59:40.210 --> 00:59:42.870
gone for Medicare for 65 year olds

00:59:42.870 --> 00:59:45.680
in 1965, it's just a harder call.

00:59:45.680 --> 00:59:47.750
It's a harder case, right?

00:59:47.750 --> 00:59:51.410
Because you're creating a potential

00:59:51.410 --> 00:59:53.470
to split the coalition that you're gonna

00:59:53.470 --> 00:59:55.450
need to expand it later.

00:59:55.450 --> 00:59:58.240
because Medicare funding is seen

00:59:58.240 --> 01:00:03.240
as more of a zero sum system of funding

01:00:03.790 --> 01:00:06.930
than the way social security is funded

01:00:06.930 --> 01:00:09.880
about which I will say more in a minute.

01:00:09.880 --> 01:00:11.960
Sometimes it should be said that

01:00:11.960 --> 01:00:13.803
this is shooting in the dark.

01:00:15.080 --> 01:00:19.460
When Bush passed his 2001 tax cut

01:00:19.460 --> 01:00:24.460
that included the estate tax repeal,

01:00:25.520 --> 01:00:27.870
it was done through budget reconciliation.

01:00:27.870 --> 01:00:30.970
And it was gonna go away 10 years later.

01:00:30.970 --> 01:00:34.421
Actually, nobody had any
idea what that would mean.

01:00:34.421 --> 01:00:37.550
And you couldn't use the
inertia of the system,

01:00:37.550 --> 01:00:39.850
because the inertia was
gonna have it go away.

01:00:39.850 --> 01:00:41.750
It was gonna be repealed back

01:00:41.750 --> 01:00:45.274
to the 2001 law if nothing was done.

01:00:45.274 --> 01:00:47.760
So, they were just gambling.

01:00:47.760 --> 01:00:51.440
And as it turned out,
the Obama Administration

01:00:51.440 --> 01:00:54.178
made almost all of it permanent as we saw.

01:00:54.178 --> 01:00:57.270
So, proximate goals, really important,

01:00:57.270 --> 01:01:01.000
but you need to always
recognize that pursuing

01:01:01.000 --> 01:01:05.993
a proximate goal may not
be good in the long run.

01:01:07.070 --> 01:01:09.975
And so, in that sense, as I said,

01:01:09.975 --> 01:01:13.170
I think it'd be hard to make the case

01:01:13.170 --> 01:01:16.160
that if it was Medicare for 65 year olds

01:01:16.160 --> 01:01:18.060
or nothing, it would have been better

01:01:18.060 --> 01:01:21.310
to have taken nothing, but it's a hard

01:01:21.310 --> 01:01:23.153
political call.

01:01:24.560 --> 01:01:26.220
Entrenching gains.

01:01:26.220 --> 01:01:29.560
Very important to entrench
gains for the long run,

01:01:29.560 --> 01:01:32.966
because otherwise, they can be undone.

01:01:32.966 --> 01:01:36.030
The classic example of this, of course,

01:01:36.030 --> 01:01:37.213
is reconstruction.

01:01:38.440 --> 01:01:40.390
The gains that were brought about

01:01:40.390 --> 01:01:41.930
as a result of the civil war,

01:01:41.930 --> 01:01:44.150
yes we got the abolition of slavery,

01:01:44.150 --> 01:01:49.150
but then we got the 14th
and 15th amendments,

01:01:49.680 --> 01:01:52.646
and the extension of the franchise,

01:01:52.646 --> 01:01:55.188
all of which was later undone,

01:01:55.188 --> 01:01:59.856
because the North was not sufficiently

01:01:59.856 --> 01:02:04.343
committed to entrenching those changers.

01:02:05.250 --> 01:02:08.200
If you want an example
of what I'm calling here,

01:02:08.200 --> 01:02:10.560
the gold standard of entrenchment,

01:02:10.560 --> 01:02:13.760
it's the way that social
security was funded.

01:02:13.760 --> 01:02:18.698
So, what FDR did was quite ingenious.

01:02:18.698 --> 01:02:21.267
They put in the system where,

01:02:21.267 --> 01:02:23.450
you know, it's a savings plan.

01:02:23.450 --> 01:02:25.340
The idea is, you work for your lifetime,

01:02:25.340 --> 01:02:27.770
you pay in, and then when you retire,

01:02:27.770 --> 01:02:29.610
you get it out.

01:02:29.610 --> 01:02:32.240
But, that's not the way it's financed.

01:02:32.240 --> 01:02:33.630
It's not the way it's financed

01:02:33.630 --> 01:02:37.330
because they wanted to start
paying out immediately.

01:02:37.330 --> 01:02:39.010
And of course, the first generation

01:02:39.010 --> 01:02:41.340
of workers in 1935 hadn't paid in.

01:02:41.340 --> 01:02:43.550
It started paying out in 1937.

01:02:43.550 --> 01:02:45.540
Those people had not paid in.

01:02:45.540 --> 01:02:49.290
And so, in reality, the current generation

01:02:49.290 --> 01:02:53.170
of workers funds the current
generation of retirees.

01:02:53.170 --> 01:02:55.010
And when people say there's an IOU

01:02:55.010 --> 01:02:56.850
in the social security trust fund,

01:02:56.850 --> 01:02:58.710
that's what they mean.

01:02:58.710 --> 01:02:59.543
Right?

01:02:59.543 --> 01:03:01.830
Now, FDR did that for two reasons.

01:03:01.830 --> 01:03:03.960
One was to build the coalition.

01:03:03.960 --> 01:03:07.060
He wanted everybody to
support it at the time.

01:03:07.060 --> 01:03:10.720
So, he wanted existing workers who hadn't

01:03:10.720 --> 01:03:11.850
paid in to support it.

01:03:11.850 --> 01:03:14.470
Of course, if you're gonna get it,

01:03:14.470 --> 01:03:17.707
you know, people about to
retire are gonna get it,

01:03:17.707 --> 01:03:18.960
they're gonna support the coalition.

01:03:18.960 --> 01:03:21.385
But he also wanted to make it impossible

01:03:21.385 --> 01:03:23.677
or very difficult to undo.

01:03:23.677 --> 01:03:24.624
Right?

01:03:24.624 --> 01:03:26.408
He said, I'm gonna fund this, he said,

01:03:26.408 --> 01:03:28.250
I'm gonna set this up in a way

01:03:28.250 --> 01:03:31.290
so that no damn fool politician

01:03:31.290 --> 01:03:33.020
can ever undo it.

01:03:33.020 --> 01:03:36.470
And so, in 2005 when George W Bush

01:03:36.470 --> 01:03:39.254
tried to undo it, he ran into

01:03:39.254 --> 01:03:41.780
the reality that, you
know, what they wanted

01:03:41.780 --> 01:03:44.530
to do was create private accounts,

01:03:44.530 --> 01:03:47.000
but instead of the money
going to the government,

01:03:47.000 --> 01:03:49.190
this was two years before
the financial crisis.

01:03:49.190 --> 01:03:51.364
It would have been pretty ugly politics

01:03:51.364 --> 01:03:53.780
if they'd gotten away with it,

01:03:53.780 --> 01:03:57.069
but instead of the money going into

01:03:57.069 --> 01:04:00.160
social security, it would be just like

01:04:00.160 --> 01:04:04.390
an IRA or like we all have.

01:04:04.390 --> 01:04:08.280
It would be going to an
account that you wouldn't

01:04:08.280 --> 01:04:10.283
privately manage account.

01:04:11.950 --> 01:04:14.140
But the problem was, to do this,

01:04:14.140 --> 01:04:16.120
they would have had to fund both systems

01:04:16.120 --> 01:04:18.130
for an entire cohort.

01:04:18.130 --> 01:04:19.040
Right?

01:04:19.040 --> 01:04:22.290
Because there's no
money in the trust fund.

01:04:22.290 --> 01:04:23.450
Right?

01:04:23.450 --> 01:04:25.940
And so, this in effect is what

01:04:25.940 --> 01:04:28.900
made the financing of social security,

01:04:28.900 --> 01:04:33.410
apart from its popularity,
made it bulletproof.

01:04:33.410 --> 01:04:37.160
So, very clever system of entrenching

01:04:37.160 --> 01:04:39.370
the program in a way that would make

01:04:39.370 --> 01:04:41.030
it extremely costly.

01:04:41.030 --> 01:04:43.500
And as it turned out, eventually the Bush

01:04:43.500 --> 01:04:45.648
people gave up.

01:04:45.648 --> 01:04:49.120
But the most important thing, and this

01:04:51.290 --> 01:04:53.280
should be evident to you from my earlier

01:04:53.280 --> 01:04:56.280
lecture on bundling is that the way

01:04:56.280 --> 01:05:01.280
in which you build protection for a policy

01:05:02.600 --> 01:05:04.350
is to build support for it,

01:05:04.350 --> 01:05:07.140
and get one of the major parties to bundle

01:05:07.140 --> 01:05:09.360
it into their major party platform.

01:05:09.360 --> 01:05:11.550
So, what protected the Civil Rights Act

01:05:11.550 --> 01:05:14.717
is it's bundled into
the democratic platform.

01:05:14.717 --> 01:05:18.140
What failed to protect reconstruction is,

01:05:18.140 --> 01:05:21.250
it was not bundled into the things

01:05:21.250 --> 01:05:24.143
that Northern republicans cared about.

01:05:25.079 --> 01:05:27.920
And of course, if you can get it bundled

01:05:27.920 --> 01:05:30.530
into the platforms of both parties,

01:05:30.530 --> 01:05:33.830
such as social security effectively is,

01:05:33.830 --> 01:05:36.118
even better.

01:05:36.118 --> 01:05:40.770
So, entrench proximate
gains for the long-term.

01:05:40.770 --> 01:05:42.660
Resources matter.

01:05:42.660 --> 01:05:46.503
Resources matter in two senses.

01:05:47.710 --> 01:05:50.473
Resources for funding the effort.

01:05:51.820 --> 01:05:54.100
If you look at something
like the estate tax

01:05:54.100 --> 01:05:56.770
repeal coalition, wealthy...

01:06:02.023 --> 01:06:05.150
Wealthy individuals put up money

01:06:05.150 --> 01:06:08.730
to fund the organizing
effort, to get that done.

01:06:08.730 --> 01:06:13.460
And we give chapter and
verse of that in our book.

01:06:13.460 --> 01:06:14.680
They paid for the meetings,

01:06:14.680 --> 01:06:19.680
they paid for the resources
to lobby, and so on.

01:06:19.980 --> 01:06:23.690
And indeed, the whole rise of

01:06:23.690 --> 01:06:26.120
neoliberalism was funded

01:06:27.110 --> 01:06:29.500
not through campaign contributions,

01:06:29.500 --> 01:06:33.870
but spending on think
tanks and other areas.

01:06:33.870 --> 01:06:35.960
So, funding efforts.

01:06:35.960 --> 01:06:37.483
And then funding the policy.

01:06:38.730 --> 01:06:41.470
So, what was so brilliant
about social security

01:06:41.470 --> 01:06:45.950
was, it was immediately
funded by existing workers.

01:06:45.950 --> 01:06:47.950
So, again, you have to think about

01:06:47.950 --> 01:06:50.400
the resources, whereas again,

01:06:50.400 --> 01:06:55.400
go back to Occupy Wall
Street that we began with.

01:06:55.510 --> 01:07:00.510
One of the reasons the
mayors of most cities

01:07:00.590 --> 01:07:02.920
just ignored them was that they knew

01:07:02.920 --> 01:07:05.460
Winter would come, they
would have no money,

01:07:05.460 --> 01:07:06.840
they would have no resources,

01:07:06.840 --> 01:07:10.110
and they would pack up and go back

01:07:10.110 --> 01:07:11.860
to wherever they came from.

01:07:11.860 --> 01:07:16.403
So, again, they hadn't any resources.

01:07:18.790 --> 01:07:21.300
And then finally, leadership matters.

01:07:21.300 --> 01:07:24.690
Leadership matters partly
because all coalitions

01:07:24.690 --> 01:07:25.523
are unstable.

01:07:25.523 --> 01:07:28.020
You need people to articulate.

01:07:28.020 --> 01:07:30.700
You need people to articulate
the moral narratives

01:07:30.700 --> 01:07:34.729
to do the work to keep people together.

01:07:34.729 --> 01:07:38.440
Again, if you think about
the Civil Rights Act.

01:07:38.440 --> 01:07:42.030
The Kennedy people, they sent civil rights

01:07:42.030 --> 01:07:47.030
legislation to capital hill in 1963.

01:07:47.280 --> 01:07:50.070
They had almost no
experience with Congress,

01:07:50.070 --> 01:07:54.010
and it soon got bottled
up in the committees.

01:07:54.010 --> 01:07:57.530
And it wasn't until Lyndon Johnson

01:07:57.530 --> 01:07:59.610
who had been the master of the Senate,

01:07:59.610 --> 01:08:02.130
this is all told chapter and verse

01:08:02.130 --> 01:08:06.360
and volume four of Caro's four volume

01:08:06.360 --> 01:08:08.400
work on Lyndon Johnson.

01:08:08.400 --> 01:08:12.885
But Johnson understood,
he's widely recognized

01:08:12.885 --> 01:08:16.265
as one of the most effective legislative

01:08:16.265 --> 01:08:20.330
politicians of the 20th century.

01:08:20.330 --> 01:08:23.610
And it was he who figured out how to do

01:08:23.610 --> 01:08:28.493
the leadership on the
hill to get that enacted.

01:08:29.540 --> 01:08:32.227
So, you need leadership
in the legislature,

01:08:32.227 --> 01:08:34.628
you need grass roots leadership.

01:08:34.628 --> 01:08:38.790
You need to mobilize support for policies,

01:08:38.790 --> 01:08:42.720
or they're they not going to get enacted.

01:08:42.720 --> 01:08:44.730
And of course, you need what's sometimes

01:08:44.730 --> 01:08:46.730
referred to by consultants

01:08:46.730 --> 01:08:49.630
as grass tops leadership.

01:08:49.630 --> 01:08:51.540
You need those Frank Blethens,

01:08:51.540 --> 01:08:55.260
and you need those Bob Johnsons to

01:08:56.600 --> 01:09:01.600
push for support if you like to articulate

01:09:03.550 --> 01:09:05.140
to act as kind of brokers

01:09:05.140 --> 01:09:08.906
between grass roots support and support

01:09:08.906 --> 01:09:12.510
in the legislature.

01:09:12.510 --> 01:09:16.960
But just to finish, effective
politics is not enough.

01:09:16.960 --> 01:09:19.900
Those six elements are not enough.

01:09:19.900 --> 01:09:22.650
If you go back through,
the story I told you

01:09:22.650 --> 01:09:24.708
about home ownership.

01:09:24.708 --> 01:09:28.040
There was a great coalition to do it

01:09:28.040 --> 01:09:30.880
that included politicians
from both parties,

01:09:30.880 --> 01:09:34.020
it included the lobbyists
from Fannie and Freddie,

01:09:34.020 --> 01:09:35.590
it included people who were going

01:09:35.590 --> 01:09:38.090
to make money out of securitization.

01:09:38.090 --> 01:09:40.430
They had not one, but
two moral narratives.

01:09:40.430 --> 01:09:43.430
The American dream of home ownership

01:09:43.430 --> 01:09:46.700
on the one hand, and then racial inclusion

01:09:46.700 --> 01:09:47.533
on the other.

01:09:47.533 --> 01:09:49.690
So, they had two moral narratives.

01:09:49.690 --> 01:09:51.370
They had great proximate goals.

01:09:51.370 --> 01:09:54.620
They could articulate how many

01:09:54.620 --> 01:09:57.860
more homes should be owned
by minority homeowners

01:09:57.860 --> 01:09:59.300
by benchmark dates.

01:09:59.300 --> 01:10:02.670
They had proximate goal
after proximate goal.

01:10:02.670 --> 01:10:04.365
They entrenched the gains indeed.

01:10:04.365 --> 01:10:06.960
One of the tragedies of it was that it

01:10:06.960 --> 01:10:09.260
was impossible to unwind when it would

01:10:09.260 --> 01:10:12.150
have been in the interests of the minority

01:10:12.150 --> 01:10:14.595
homeowners to unwind it in the ways

01:10:14.595 --> 01:10:17.400
that Geanokopolis was proposing.

01:10:17.400 --> 01:10:21.100
So, it became a kind of
pathologically entrenched.

01:10:22.257 --> 01:10:25.240
The resources were brilliantly generated

01:10:25.240 --> 01:10:27.772
by the securitization, which created

01:10:27.772 --> 01:10:30.510
a study cycle of liquidity

01:10:32.290 --> 01:10:34.430
to produce more of the activity

01:10:34.430 --> 01:10:38.880
until the music stopped,
to use Blinder's line.

01:10:38.880 --> 01:10:40.270
And then there was leadership.

01:10:40.270 --> 01:10:44.570
There was leadership from
both political parties.

01:10:44.570 --> 01:10:47.020
There was leadership in the country.

01:10:47.020 --> 01:10:51.310
And there was plenty of
support from business

01:10:51.310 --> 01:10:54.980
leaders who saw that there
was money to be made.

01:10:54.980 --> 01:10:57.507
So, building blocks of effective

01:10:57.507 --> 01:11:00.430
distributive politics are important,

01:11:00.430 --> 01:11:03.180
but they're not a
substitute for good policy,

01:11:03.180 --> 01:11:06.980
and you can indeed have
bad policy that meets

01:11:06.980 --> 01:11:10.810
all six of these criteria.

01:11:10.810 --> 01:11:13.710
And that would be the
poster child for that.

01:11:13.710 --> 01:11:16.430
So, next we're gonna look at good policies

01:11:16.430 --> 01:11:18.130
that can be enacted by paying

01:11:18.130 --> 01:11:20.793
attention to these six building blocks.

01:11:21.899 --> 01:11:24.933
And that's what we'll
start with on Thursday.

